data.content:
Here are the idiomatic MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | Subsumes both count checks; failure message shows *expected: 3, actual: N* instead of just *false* |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | *(merged above)* | Redundant once you assert exact count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(...)` | Failure says *"expected non-null"* instead of *"expected true"* |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` | *(keep as-is)* | MSTest's `CollectionAssert` has no predicate-based `All`; LINQ here is fine |

The general rule: prefer **specific** assertions (`AreEqual`, `IsNotNull`, `CollectionAssert.*`) over `Assert.IsTrue` — they produce much better failure messages.
